{"nmem_brain_package": "1.0", "manifest": {"id": "c7ce83eb-20dd-40b0-a90a-80caa7495904", "name": "python-best-practices", "display_name": "Python Best Practices", "description": "Curated knowledge on Pythonic patterns, common gotchas, performance tips, and project setup workflows. Covers type hints, async, error handling, naming conventions, and tooling.", "version": "1.0.0", "author": "neural-memory", "license": "CC-BY-4.0", "tags": ["python", "best-practices", "patterns", "typing", "async"], "category": "programming", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442723+00:00", "exported_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442723+00:00", "nmem_version": "4.33.0", "stats": {"neuron_count": 20, "synapse_count": 10, "fiber_count": 0}, "size_bytes": 12001, "size_tier": "micro", "content_hash": "sha256:bc232c8dd3a953444739b58e151c74a49b999d7d376f6d5a7c65a3d1cd25dd66", "scan_summary": {"risk_level": "clean", "finding_count": 0, "safe": true}, "rating_avg": 0.0, "rating_count": 0, "download_count": 0}, "snapshot": {"brain_id": "python-best-practices", "brain_name": "python-best-practices", "config": {}, "exported_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442451+00:00", "fibers": [], "metadata": {"quality": "curated", "source": "seed-generator"}, "neurons": [{"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Chose dataclasses over plain dicts for domain models because they provide type safety, immutability (frozen=True), and IDE autocompletion with zero runtime overhead", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442334+00:00", "id": "py-d1", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "architecture"], "type": "decision", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442334+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Chose Pydantic for API boundary validation and dataclasses for internal domain models — Pydantic handles untrusted input, dataclasses handle trusted internal data", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442352+00:00", "id": "py-d2", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "validation"], "type": "decision", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442352+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Chose pathlib over os.path because it provides an object-oriented API, handles cross-platform paths correctly, and chains operations fluently", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442355+00:00", "id": "py-d3", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "filesystem"], "type": "decision", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442355+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Chose f-strings over .format() and % formatting because they are faster, more readable, and support expressions inline since Python 3.6", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442357+00:00", "id": "py-d4", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "strings"], "type": "decision", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442357+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Chose asyncio + aiohttp over threading for I/O-bound concurrency because cooperative scheduling avoids lock contention and scales to thousands of connections", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442359+00:00", "id": "py-d5", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "async"], "type": "decision", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442359+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Type hints don't slow Python at runtime — they're stripped by the interpreter. The cost is zero but the gain in IDE support and mypy catches real bugs before production", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442360+00:00", "id": "py-i1", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "typing"], "type": "insight", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442360+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Mutable default arguments are shared across all calls: `def f(items=[])` creates ONE list. Always use `None` as default and create inside the function body", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442362+00:00", "id": "py-i2", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "gotchas"], "type": "insight", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442362+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Context managers (with statement) guarantee cleanup even on exceptions. Use them for files, locks, database connections — anything that needs deterministic release", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442363+00:00", "id": "py-i3", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "patterns"], "type": "insight", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442363+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "List comprehensions are 30-40% faster than equivalent for-loops because the iteration happens in C code. But readability beats speed — switch to loops if the comprehension exceeds one line", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442365+00:00", "id": "py-i4", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "performance"], "type": "insight", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442365+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Python's GIL means CPU-bound threads don't parallelize. Use multiprocessing for CPU work, asyncio for I/O work, and threading only for C extensions that release the GIL", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442366+00:00", "id": "py-i5", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "concurrency"], "type": "insight", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442366+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Root cause: bare `except:` catches SystemExit and KeyboardInterrupt, making scripts unkillable. Fix: always catch specific exceptions like `except ValueError as e:`", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442368+00:00", "id": "py-e1", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "error-handling"], "type": "error", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442368+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Root cause: `import *` silently overwrites local names. A library update can break your code without changing your files. Fix: always import explicitly", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442369+00:00", "id": "py-e2", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "imports"], "type": "error", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442369+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Root cause: comparing with `==` to None/True/False fails for objects that override __eq__. Fix: use `is None`, `is True` for identity checks", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442371+00:00", "id": "py-e3", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "gotchas"], "type": "error", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442371+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "PEP 8 naming: snake_case for functions/variables, PascalCase for classes, SCREAMING_SNAKE for constants. Private: _single_leading_underscore. Name-mangling: __double_leading", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442374+00:00", "id": "py-f1", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "style"], "type": "fact", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442374+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Virtual environments isolate project dependencies. Always use `python -m venv .venv` or `uv venv` — never install packages globally. Pin versions in requirements.txt or pyproject.toml", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442375+00:00", "id": "py-f2", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "packaging"], "type": "fact", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442375+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "The walrus operator `:=` (Python 3.8+) assigns inside expressions: `if (n := len(items)) > 10:` — useful in while-loops and comprehension filters but hurts readability if overused", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442376+00:00", "id": "py-f3", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "syntax"], "type": "fact", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442376+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Python project setup: 1) pyproject.toml with [project] metadata 2) src/ layout 3) uv or pip for deps 4) ruff for lint+format 5) mypy for types 6) pytest for tests 7) pre-commit hooks", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442378+00:00", "id": "py-w1", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "tooling"], "type": "workflow", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442378+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Debugging workflow: 1) Reproduce with minimal case 2) Add breakpoint() 3) Step through with pdb commands (n/s/c/p) 4) Check locals/type 5) Fix and add regression test", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442379+00:00", "id": "py-w2", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "debugging"], "type": "workflow", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442379+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "EAFP (Easier to Ask Forgiveness than Permission) is Pythonic: try the operation, catch the exception. LBYL (Look Before You Leap) uses if-checks first. EAFP is preferred in Python because exceptions are cheap and race-condition safe", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442381+00:00", "id": "py-c1", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "philosophy"], "type": "concept", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442381+00:00"}, {"access_count": 1, "activation": 0.5, "brain_id": "seed", "content": "Generators yield values lazily — they produce one item at a time and suspend between yields. This means processing a 10GB file uses constant memory. Use generators for any pipeline that processes items sequentially", "created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442382+00:00", "id": "py-c2", "salience": 0.6, "state": "active", "tags": ["python", "patterns"], "type": "concept", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442382+00:00"}], "synapses": [{"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442405+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "9e19f1cf-5121-4167-a649-0d0a68ffed07", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-d2", "target_id": "py-i1", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.8}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442413+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "4be3d217-0064-4ec2-b194-48ea32f14bc9", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-i2", "target_id": "py-d1", "type": "caused_by", "weight": 0.7}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442417+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "9c5556b7-6c9d-4233-8e3f-823ea7fc8c9e", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-e1", "target_id": "py-i3", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.6}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442419+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "07bc27f3-711f-409d-8c5a-ea05ac2b29c2", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-i5", "target_id": "py-d5", "type": "caused_by", "weight": 0.9}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442423+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "afd4543c-067c-43de-a50a-eac3952cd1d5", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-i4", "target_id": "py-c2", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.7}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442425+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "623aad25-e47f-423d-a04f-016f20e8059e", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-f1", "target_id": "py-w1", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.5}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442428+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "52aedf6a-507d-403a-91cf-15b4b67045ea", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-e2", "target_id": "py-f2", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.6}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442431+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "656ffbe1-6e4f-4236-908f-c1b361d91c8c", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-c1", "target_id": "py-e1", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.7}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442433+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "0b744d48-c1a5-4f6b-a833-ae1b6b794f08", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-d3", "target_id": "py-w2", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.4}, {"created_at": "2026-04-05T17:15:35.442435+00:00", "direction": "unidirectional", "id": "2c840a79-7720-4f54-ac9e-0be4a0af5889", "reinforced_count": 1, "source_id": "py-e3", "target_id": "py-i1", "type": "related_to", "weight": 0.5}], "version": "1"}}